items.name: Digital Diffusion
items.description:
Higher quality 2.1 images!

Thank you for checking out the new and improved digital diffusion! This model is a general purpose 2.1 model that does well in many styles and themes. I really hope you enjoy the model, and please share what you can create with it!

Basic prompting guide:

This model might prompt closer to SD 1.5, since you don't need overly complicated prompts to get really cool images. The two most important tokens are digital art and photograph. These control what kind of image you are generating. It's pretty self explanatory what they do as well.

There are other tokens that can improve your images or make them feel a certain way, or are just fun to experiment with. Here are some of my favorites!

  • Portrait

  • Landcsape

  • Vehicle

  • Cinematic

  • Dramatic

  • Fantasy

  • Particles

  • Steampunk

  • Moody

  • Dark

  • Bright

  • Calm

  • Sunrise

FOR V1: the prompting guide to better understand how to use the model to it's fullest extent, or at least to the extent I have discovered.

items.name: Cayna from In the Land of Leadale
items.description:
Cayna from The Land of Leadale I trained this cause I found the girlpack for the anime didn't render the minute intricacies.

This is the 1st usable Lora I made so say if there were some issues. I trained it with NAI so it should work on a variety of models which my examples should show as I tried it on over 10 diff models.

Keywords: cayna, blue eyes, short hair, black pants, pointy ears, bangs, hairband, hair ornament, blonde hair, cape, bodysuit

blonde hair is not needed 100% of the time, but occasionally it renders her with brown hair if not included which happened about 2% of the time in my testing.

It renders her normal outfit, and it can render her in a wetsuit from the 11th(or was it 10th) episode.

If you put hairband, hair ornament, and headband in the negatives there is a chance it will render without them

to get the wetsuit use bodysuit, and put the rest of the clothing in the negatives.

It is trained on 52 images official art from the novels covers, magazines, and screen caps from the anime, and I think 1 or 2 were fan art.

The images I generated as an example were done on the following models. NAI, anythinv3, anything v4.5, deliberate realistic v10, cyber realistic v12, and neverendingDream

modelVersions.name: v2
modelVersions.description:
Complete overhaul - entirely new dataset, reg images, settings, etc. Still "good" but not "great"

Some important notes:

  • Significantly better odds of achieving the hairstyle VS version 1, but less respect towards original image.

  • Weights needed to achieve hairstyle with minimal image alteration vary wildly on a per-image basis (anywhere from 0.2 to 1.0, even on the same checkpoint + hair color)

  • Works best on illustrative, realistic, and photographic models

  • Anime models tend to keep/add the center-forehead bangs regardless of weight

  • Doesn't work well for Asians (keeps the center-forehead bangs) or Indians (just doesn't apply)

  • Still some struggles with brunettes (usually just need higher weights for this hair color, e.g. 0.5 to 1.25)

  • Has a strong desire to significantly alter image/facial features, although it tends to adhere to the overall style even so.

  • You may want to add "cleavage" and/or "nsfw" to negative prompts

  • Not tested on dudes. All training data images are of women of various natural hair colors and ancestries.

modelVersions.name: v1
modelVersions.description:
Important/TLDR Stuff

  • Trigger word is tfft

  • Calibrated to function best-ish at 1.0 weight, but weight may need to be adjusted based on your needs (in particular, increased for brunettes and decreased for redheads; working on this).

  • Does not apply very often/well on some photographic checkpoints, ESPECIALLY for Brunettes for some reason (e.g. Realistic Vision 2.0, Analog Madness V3). Works pretty well on redheads, moderately well on black hair / blonde hair / asians, and just refuses to apply to brunettes more than 10% of the time.

  • Other than that, works pretty well on realistic and illustrative/anime checkpoints. Weight can probably safely be lowered on non-anime illustrative checkpoints like Lyriel.

  • Should play well with other LoRAs EXCEPT POSSIBLY Character LoRAs. Might conflict with some character LoRAs - haven't tested this too extensively yet (Chisato refused to heed it, for example). May need to lower weight of either/both LoRAs if there is an initial conflict.

  • Shouldn't impact style of checkpoints/LoRAs/LyCORISs. Tested with a number of checkpoints and a few style LoRAs (sometimes multiple style LoRAs at once), little if any impact found.

  • You will need to negatively prompt for "nsfw" and/or "naked" on SFW imagery. Sorry. It's surprisingly keen on stripping clothing.

items.name: Peter Pan - Tinkerbell
items.description:
If you like the LoRa, please feel free to share your generated images here and leave a review (or at least a rating) for the sake of motivation and stuff ;D

For usage guidance, look into the About this version box for more information and click on Show more to get all trigger words and combinations (The trigger words in the Details box are a pain to manage).

Please contact me here on civitAi or on Twitter if you want to provide the LoRa in a generation service.

About

Well, a friend of mine really likes Tinkerbell, so to make it easier to explain what all this generative ai art stuff is about, I created this LoRa (and in the process watched, uuuh I mean skipped, both Peter Pan movies for the first time in my life, to be honest I don't understand why she likes Tinkerbell... as far as I understood, she's kind of an asshole character, but who am I to judge ;D) so she can happily generate images of her favorite character.

Training

I collected 31 training images from both original movies, I thought about adding the 3D movie stuff, but Tinkerbell just doesn't look like she does in the original movies.

items.description:
This LoRa retains some style elements from my earlier Zelrik and Venabaris LoRa but was designed to play better with darker skin tones. Of course this is the first release and I may release an update later. Trigger word is Itzayan but you don't really need it. Works even on a low weight, I recommend you start at 0.6 or even lower.

PS: you might still want to put 'darkskin' or 'tanned' in prompt if you want darker skin colors depending on the base model you're working with. I know I always have to at least.

For exclusive/early access to some of my LoRa and other goodies, feel free to visit my patreon page:

https://www.patreon.com/the_real_zoi_ai

The same conditions apply as my earlier releases:

  • Do not use for commercial purposes before asking me

  • Please credit me when it's obvious that you're making heavy use of my LoRa.

items.name: S≈çichir≈ç Yamamoto Style [Foreheads Edition]
items.description:
Makes images in style similar to S≈çichir≈ç Yamamoto famous for his series "Teasing Master Takagi-san" and "In the Heart of Kunoichi Tsubaki" to name a few.

How to use
Recommended LoRA strength is around 0.8 to 1.4, higher values generally needed on models with more realism blended in. As of version 1.1 the "forehead" tag is more optional but can still be used if you want to strengthen the style at lower weights.
Different samplers gives different looks, Euler A gives a more clean look while Karras M tends to draw more on the sketch data - experiment to see what you like best.

Don't forget to review and upload your own images, it's always fun to see what you're creating!
Like my LoRAs and want more? Please consider a small tip towards my electricity bill and further training >.<

Misc
Trained on NAI at 512 res. Dataset of 81 solo character images.
All images are raw (slightly cherrypicked), txt2img gens, no post work done.

models used

The results of your generations are dependent on the additional LoRAs, weights, and models you use, so it may not work or come out as consistent as my sample images. Other reasons may include me using xformers, token merging, and a modified DPM++ 2M Karras sampler. You'll also notice that my prompt includes <lyco:. Note that all my LoRA files are located within my LyCORIS folder. If the model is labeled as a LoRA, it's a simple LoRA. If it's specified as a LyCORIS, it's a LoHa.

v0.1

Weight: 1.0

Trigger + Appearance: shiba kuukaku, (prosthesis, prosthetic arm:1.2), bandages, large breasts

Default Outfit: red dress, cleavage

The amputee prompt might work, it might not, same could be said for her prosthetic arm.

This is the first LoRA I trained on my laptop, this time using Lykon's AnyLoRA checkpoint as a training model. The result is mid, but I'm not disappointed. I realized that I had messed up on one of the settings after checking its metadata, but it's okay because it's all part of the fun experience that is baking a model for ~6 hours. I'll be learning from this to train another character tomorrow.
